Breaking news: Our Cosmic Visitor Huge Asteroid 2014 JO25
In our Solar System there are perhaps more than billion huge, stray meteors that would cause serious consequences should they collide.
Left over from the sun’s formation and having either closed or open orbits, these objects could, at times, cross Earth’s path.
With a diameter of 650 meters, asteroid 2014 JO25 is such a visitor, and today at 14:24 will pass by Earth, at its closest point 1.75 million kilometers away.
As time passes, we have started to hear such types of reports more and more.
The most important cause of this are developments in observational techniques and tools.
Consequently, we are able to identify small asteroids which could not previously be identified.
For example, last January a bus-sized asteroid passed by within half the distance between the Earth and the Moon (~250,000 km).
And more importantly, the asteroid could be identified only a couple days before it passed by.
That is to say, we could have more cosmic buses coming at us.
Just imagine: What would you do if you learnt that a 20 meter diameter asteroid would fall in the middle of your neighborhood?
Actually, an asteroid of that size would not wipe out your neighborhood, but it’d probably blast out all of the buildings’ windows.
That would be due to the asteroid’s shock waves as it exploded in the atmosphere.
For example, the asteroid that landed in Russia in 2013 was of that size and was enough to blast out buildings’ windows in a couple of cities.
However, if there is was an asteroid of a 100-meter diameter targeting your neighborhood, I would advise to get up to 50 km away.
Specific criteria, such as an asteroid’s size and collision angle, are the factors that would determine the depth of its crater and the damage that its impact would cause.
Let’s have a look at a couple of scenarios from the European Space Agency’s simulation.
If an asteroid having a diameter of 100 meters collided with Earth at an angle of 45 degrees and at a speed of 60 km/s, it would form a crater 250 meters deep and 1200 meters in diameter.
The collision would be the equivalent to an earthquake at six on the Richter scale and, even if you were 10 km away from the impact point, you would have third-degree burns on your body.
And, 50 km away there would be bits of broken window glass.
If a 1-km diameter asteroid landed, the situation would be much worse.
If such an asteroid collided the with the Earth with the same angle and speed, it would form a crater 600 meters deep and 12 km in diameter.
That is an entire neighborhood turning into a crater and disappearing all at once.
The heat created by such a collision would cause third-degree burns on your body even if you were 100 km away from the collision point.
The impact would be equivalent to an earthquake of magnitude of 8 on the Richter scale.
The damage caused by an asteroid depends not only on the asteroid’s chemical compound, but also on the rock formations at the point of impact.
The above values are for a scenario of a hard, rock-like asteroid falling onto an area of sedimentary rock.
If an asteroid mostly composed of iron landed on a surface of cold lava, the crater size would be three-times bigger and consequently, the disaster would be much greater.
Sixty-six million years ago something worse happened to the dinosaurs in the disaster resulting from the impact of an asteroid 10 km in diameter.
That asteroid’s led to the extermination of 75% of all sea and land creatures.
If an asteroid of the size that would have destroyed the dinosaurs was on a collision course with the Earth, the safest option would be to leave the planet.
Tons of objects from space are falling to earth.
Most of these are burnt to ash in the atmosphere.
Some meteors, popularly known as shooting stars, are big enough to glow in atmosphere as they burn.
Let’s end our article with some other, relaxing news.
According to studies, no asteroid large enough to cause serious destruction is expected to collide with the Earth in the next 300–400 years.
As creatures with an average lifetime of 70 years, I’m sure you are somewhat relieved.
