Don’t dive just anywhere
Chairman of the Turkish Neurosurgical Association Prof. Dr. Yusuf Sukru Caglar warned swimmers not to dive where they are unsure of the depth, or anywhere not more than two meters deep.
Every year, thousands of people face the risk of paralysis because of neck fractures or spinal cord injuries due to diving into shallow waters.
Neck fractures most frequently occur in the fifth or sixth vertebra.
These fractures especially affect the nerves feeding the arm and leg muscles, as well as the respiratory muscles.
Prof. Dr. Caglar commented "The most important area in these kinds of accidents is our cervical vertebra region which is either cut through by fractured pieces or rendered dysfunctional by being squeezed."
"And incorrect first aid in response to spinal injuries not only increases the damage, but also could lead to death" he said.
Diving into water ranks fourth in the causes of spinal injuries.
The average age is 20–29, and most victims are male.
Prof. Dr. Çağlar "One shouldn’t be diving into water into which they can’t see".
"No matter how well one dives, there still could be a serious injury" he said.
Prof. Dr. Çağlar continued:
Depending on the level of the vertebra at which the damage occurs, paralysis of varying degrees might occur in the arms and the legs.
You may be able to swim, but the water might be deceiving.
A place that looks deep to you might be shallow.
Due to warning signs placed along sea shores in the USA and Australia, there has been a 70% decrease in swimmers’ diving injuries.
Prof. Dr. Çağlar added that "Although Turkey has twenty-eight provinces having a coastline, unfortunately there isn’t one single warning sign anywhere outside of Istanbul."
"In response to such devastating accidents, each summer there has to be informative illuminated signs or information boards along sea shores and near pools as part of a social awareness project conducted by each province’s health directorate" he said.
TURKISH Neurosurgical Association Spinal and Periferic Neurosurgery Group Chairman Prof. Dr. Kadir Kotil, suggested the following in the case of any such injury:
The first thing to do, as soon as an accident happens, is to call 112.
The neck must be kept stable, not be moved, and to the extent possible held in place by a hard collar.
The supply of air must be ensured and the patient must be laid down on their side in order to drain out any water that has entered their lungs.
The patient should not be suspended by the legs to drain the water.
No attempt should be made to correct any deformity in the patient’s neck.
The vertebrate of the neck may have been fractured.
If the spinal cord had not yet been damaged, an improper positioning of the neck during first aid, or any moving of the patient, may cause fractured bone pieces to put pressure on the spinal cord or damage it by cutting.
